===========================================================
📁 FILE SYSTEM NAVIGATION & MANAGEMENT
===========================================================

pwd                                 → Show current working directory
ls                                  → List files and directories
ls -l                               → List with detailed info (permissions, size, date)
ls -a                               → List all files including hidden files
ls -lh                              → Human-readable file sizes
tree                                → Display directory structure in tree format

cd /path/to/dir                     → Change directory
cd ~                                → Go to home directory
cd ..                               → Move one directory up
cd -                                → Go back to previous directory

mkdir <dir>                         → Create a new directory
mkdir -p /path/to/new/dir           → Create nested directories

rmdir <dir>                         → Remove an empty directory
rm -rf <dir>                        → Forcefully remove a directory and its contents

touch <file>                        → Create an empty file
cp <source> <destination>           → Copy file to another location
cp -r <dir1> <dir2>                 → Copy directory recursively
mv <old> <new>                      → Rename or move a file/directory
rm <file>                           → Delete a file

cat <file>                          → View file contents
less <file>                         → View file page by page
head <file>                         → Show first 10 lines of a file
tail <file>                         → Show last 10 lines of a file
tail -f <file>                      → Follow file updates in real time

find / -name <file>                 → Search for a file by name
find /home -type f -name "*.txt"    → Find all .txt files under /home
locate <file>                       → Quickly find a file (uses database)
updatedb                            → Update file location database for ‘locate’

du -h                               → Show disk usage of directories
du -sh *                            → Show size of each item in current directory
df -h                               → Show disk space usage (human-readable)
df -Th                              → Show disk usage with filesystem type
lsblk                               → List all storage devices and partitions
mount                               → Show mounted filesystems
mount /dev/sdX1 /mnt                → Mount a device manually
umount /mnt                         → Unmount a device

file <filename>                     → Identify file type
stat <filename>                     → Display detailed file information (size, modify time)
basename /path/file                 → Show filename only
dirname /path/file                  → Show directory name from full path

ln <target> <linkname>              → Create hard link
ln -s <target> <linkname>           → Create symbolic (soft) link

history                             → Show command history
history | grep <keyword>            → Search history for a specific command

clear                               → Clear the terminal screen
reset                               → Reset terminal display
